{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/a-simple-guide-to-knowing-your-neural-network-and-activation-8d98ebfcd3fd", "time": 1683005486.5339599, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/a-simple-guide-to-knowing-your-neural-network-and-activation-8d98ebfcd3fd/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "A simple guide to knowing your neural network and activation. | by Milan George | Towards Data Science", "h1": "A simple guide to knowing your neural network and activation.", "description": "To better understand the intents and purposes of activation functions, let us analyze an equivalent model within ourselves \u2014 neurons ( the inspiration for neural networks in the first place). A\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["To better understand the intents and purposes of activation functions, let us analyze an equivalent model within ourselves \u2014 neurons ( the inspiration for neural networks in the first place). A biological neural network simply consists of a cell body, dendrites (inputs from neurons) and axons (output to other neurons). A useful term would be synapses which from the contact point where one neuron communicates with the other. The dendrites are covered with the synapses formed from the ends of the axons from other neurons. The synapses from all the dendrites are accumulated in the cell body which determines the status of the cell \u2014 activated/unactivated based on the threshold ( which is analogous to various activation functions)the accumulation crosses. These synapses then traverse the axon on to other neurons communicating along the way.", "An ANN does maintain the integrity of its biological equivalent albeit with a few more terms.", "output = \u03a3 ( weights * inputs ) + bias", "This follows a linear equation of y = mx + c where the weight corresponds to \u2018m\u2019 and bias corresponds to \u2018c\u2019", "Weights, typically synaptic weights represent the strength of one neuron on another making the overall connection stronger.", "Serving as an intercept, a bias term conforms the network to practical instances instead of idealistic ones. If the bias term were to be absent, the trained point will pass only through the origin which is too simple an analysis. A network tends to be more robust with a bias term as it is open to new ways of consideration and fitting. Moreover, it determines the point at which the activation function will come into effect.", "Now that we did a basic walkthrough of how the biological and artificial neural networks compare, we will take a look at the various activation functions out there and examine their advantages and limitations.", "Each activation function takes a single value and performs a mathematical operation on it.", "However, it is rarely implemented due to the following limitations:", "Although similar to the sigmoid function, the tanh function solves one of its limitations: the non-zero-centred output.", "The Leaky ReLU attempts to solve the limitation of the dying ReLU problem.", "Avoid the sigmoid function. You can opt for the ReLU or the Leaky ReLU ( as an alternative to the ReLU function). Though, monitor your learning rates.", "You can give Tanh a shot but it\u2019s likely to produce a less optimal result than its ReLU counterparts.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Dev \u2022 Art \u2022 Jazz A curious developer , a voracious reader and a passionate jazz and art enthusiast. These elements help maintain my balance. \ud83c\udf43"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F8d98ebfcd3fd&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fa-simple-guide-to-knowing-your-neural-network-and-activation-8d98ebfcd3fd&source=post_pa